Description of the RICS HomeBuyer Service Typical house diagram

RICS is the world's leading qualification when it comes to professional standards in land, property and construction.

In a world where more and more people, governments, banks and commercial organisations demand greater certainty of professional standards and ethics, attaining RICS status is the recognised mark of property professionalism.

Over 100,000 property professionals working in the major established and emerging economies of the world have already recognised the importance of securing RICS status by becoming members.

RICS is an independent professional body originally established in the UK by Royal Charter. Since 1868, RICS has been committed to setting and upholding the highest standards of excellence and integrity ­ providing impartial, authoritative advice on key issues affecting businesses and society.

This HomeBuyer Report is produced by an RICS surveyor who has written this report for you to use. If you decide not to act on the advice in this report, you do this at your own risk.

The HomeBuyer Report aims to help you:

make a reasoned and informed decision on whether to go ahead with buying the property;

make an informed decision on what is a reasonable price to pay for the property; take account of any repairs or replacements the property needs; and

consider what further advice you should take before committing to purchase the property.

Any extra services we provide that are not covered by the terms and conditions of this report must be covered by a separate contract.

We inspect the inside and outside of the main building and all permanent outbuildings, but we do not force or open up the fabric. We also inspect the parts of the electricity, gas/oil, water, heating and drainage services that can be seen, but we do not test them.

To help describe the condition of the home, we give condition ratings to the main parts (the 'elements') of the building, garage and some parts outside. Some elements can be made up of several different parts.

In the element boxes in parts E, F, G and H, we describe the part that has the worst condition rating first and then briefly outline the condition of the other parts. The condition ratings are described as follows.

Defects that are serious and/or need to be repaired, replaced or investigated urgently.

Defects that need repairing or replacing but are not considered to be either serious or urgent. The property must be maintained in the normal way.

No repair is currently needed. The property must be maintained in the normal way.

Not inspected (see 'Important note' below).

The report covers matters that, in the surveyor's opinion, need to be dealt with or may affect the value of the property.

Important note: We carry out only a visual inspection. This means that we do not take up carpets, floor coverings or floorboards, move furniture or remove the contents of cupboards. Also, we do not remove secured panels or undo electrical fittings.

We inspect roofs, chimneys and other surfaces on the outside of the building from ground level and, if necessary, from neighbouring public property and with the help of binoculars.

We inspect the roof structure from inside the roof space if there is access (although we do not move or lift insulation material, stored goods or other contents). We examine floor surfaces and under­floor spaces so far as there is safe access to these (although we do not move or lift furniture, floor coverings or other contents). We are not able to assess the condition of the inside of any chimney, boiler or other flues.

We note in our report if we are not able to check any parts of the property that the inspection would normally cover. If we are concerned about these parts, the report will tell you about any further investigations that are needed.

We do not report on the cost of any work to put right defects or make recommendations on how these repairs should be carried out. Some maintenance and repairs we suggest may be expensive.

E3 Rainwater pipes and gutters

Limitations to inspection

Although a condition rating has been allocated, my inspection of the roofs was restricted as it was from ground level.

There are none.

Roof coverings

The main sloping roof is covered with concrete pan­tiles over a secondary waterproof barrier (roofing felt).

The roof tiles are the original installation and appears in good condition when inspected through binoculars at ground level.

The undercloak supporting the roof tiles to the gable end wall, is most probably consisting of asbestos containing materials (ACM). This is not an issue unless roof repairs are ever required at this verge detail.

Asbestos should only be removed by licensed operators.

There is a lead valley gutter detail to front elevation low level roof which is a shared roof with the attached neighbour.

There is some lichen/moss debris within the lead valley gutter that should be cleared out at some point in the future before it collects in the guttering and blocks the downpipes.

This is a minor issue, that you should just be aware of.

The rainwater pipes and gutters are made of plastic.

No repair is currently needed. The property must be maintained in the normal way, which includes cleaning out debris on an annual basis to maintain water flow to the gutters.

This includes the rear conservatory.

E4

Main walls

Property address

The outside walls are built of brick and block, with an air gap between the inside and outside faces (called a cavity wall). Where visible, the walls have a barrier against dampness rising from the ground (called a damp­proof course or DPC) consisting of a meshed polypropylene.

It is assumed that there is cavity insulation given the recent construction age of the property.

The rear wall has an extractor fan hole above the conservatory roof, which has its outer grille flaps missing. I'm not certain what this extractor outlet serves or that it is currently used, as I could find no evidence internally as to what it could be connected to.

The unit needs to be repaired to prevent bird, insect or vermin access or removed and infilled with brickwork if it is no longer in use.

The double­glazed windows are made of Upvc and appear to be from the original construction of nearly twenty years ago. This means that these windows have exceeded their life expectancy and will probably require replacement or at least the double glazed sealed units replaced, in the next few years.

The rear conservatory is approx. five years old and is in good structural condition.

The pleated blinds to the ceiling and windows have slightly deteriorated as some of the blinds have started to crease and loose their shape at the edges. These may be beyond repair and may need to be replaced in due course.

F1 Roof structure

F2

Ceilings

Limitations to inspection

Although a condition rating has been allocated, the inspection of the concrete and timber floors was restricted because of floor coverings to all areas.

The roof is in good condition.

The roof structure is built of timber trusses and is well ventilated.

The roof space has approx 100mm thermal insulation on the top of the ceiling but this does not meet current building regulation guidelines of 270mm overall thickness.

There is chipboard decking through the centre of the loft that is used for storage.

The under­felt to the roof tiles is intact and I did not see any sign of roof leaks. However, the original soil and vent pipe has been removed and replaced with an internal 'durgo vent valve' and the original roof vent and cowl has been left in position. The under­felt had been originally poorly cut to allow the pipe to pass through the roof and has never been sealed off properly.

Whilst I could not see any rainwater penetration, this pipe and cowl remains a minor weak point in the roof for allowing insects in to the loft and ought to be removed and sealed off correctly. However, given that there is a conservatory below the roof to the rear, access to this would be difficult and would need to be undertaken from the front elevation.

This is not an essential repair requirement but just one that you need to be aware of. There is a light within the loft that is operated from the landing below.

There isn't a loft ladder to access the loft space.

The only other minor observation is that there is a missing piece of block­work/mortar to the cavity party wall with the neighbour. This does not affect stability the roof or wall.

The ceilings are made of modern plasterboard and are in good condition.

A textured decorative coating covers the ceilings to all rooms. This may contain small amounts of asbestos fibres and if disturbed, they could be a safety hazard (see section J3 Risks).

Ceilings coated in artex prior to 1999 may contain asbestos containing material (ACM's). If you redecorate the ceiling, you should wear the appropriate dust masks and be careful not to dislodge any of the textured coatings.

A test and report system exists to check for ACM's that will clarify the artex content before undertaking any repairs, should you wish to do so.

If you decide to disturb or remove the ceilings, this should be undertaken by a specialist asbestos removal company.

G1 Electricity

Services are generally hidden within the construction of the property. This means that we can only inspect the visible parts of the available services, and we do not carry out specialist tests. The visual inspection cannot assess the services to make sure they work efficiently and safely, and meet modern standards.

Limitations to inspection

It is not possible to verify the condition of the underground supply pipe from the water authority mains to the point of entry into the property. This length of pipework is typically the responsibility of the owner. However, being a relatively new property, I do not think that this will be an issue for concern.

Safety warning: The Electrical Safety Council recommends that you should get a registered electrician to check the property and its electrical fittings at least every ten years, or on change of occupancy. All electrical installation work undertaken after 1 January 2005 should have appropriate certification. For more advice contact the Electrical Safety Council.

There is a mains electricity supply and the meter is located in the external meter cabinet fixed on the front elevation. The electricity supply was on when I inspected.

The consumer unit is located at high level in the ground floor cloakroom and it appears to be the original installation.

It does contain Residual Current Device (RCDs), which is a safety feature that protects from electric shocks and cuts out the supply to faulty wiring.

There is an electrical box fitted upside down in the cloakroom below the consumer unit. It is not clear what this is for and it is a concern that it has been refixed upside down after the wall panel installation (See section F9).

There are some loose cables at high level adjacent to the front entrance door. It may be a disconnected movement sensor but this needs to be investigated further.

There is underfloor heating to the ground floor. However, I did not see this in operation and I understand from the present owners that they do not use it, as they stated it gets too warm.

It could be that the underfloor heating might not work. Depending upon the date of installation, the electrical underfloor heating can stop working if there's a break in the cables. This should be investigated by an electrician to verify that it is working satisfactorily.

As I was not shown a current electrical inspection certificate, I have had to report this section as a condition rating 3 and would recommend that an electrician undertakes an electrical test and inspection and issues a certificate of compliance.

This is always recommended for every 10 years or whenever a new owner purchases a property.

You can find a qualified electrician to test the electricity by searching the Electrical Safety Council's website http://www.esc.org.uk/public/findanelectrician/

G2

Gas/oil

Safety warning: All gas and oil appliances and equipment should regularly be inspected, tested, maintained and serviced by a registered 'competent person' and in line with the manufacturer's instructions. This is important to make sure that the equipment is working correctly, to limit the risk of fire and carbon monoxide poisoning and to prevent carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gases from leaking into the air. For more advice contact the Gas Safe Register for gas installations, and OFTEC for oil installations.

There is a mains gas supply, and the meter and control valve are located in the external meter cabinet at low level to the front elevation.

The boiler is located within a kitchen wall cupboard and appears to be the original installation. It is therefore past its effective life­span and will require replacement in due course.

There is an independent mains water supply to the property. The external stop valve is in the pavement to the front elevation.

Stopcocks can become stiff and difficult to operate. It would be prudent therefore to periodically open and close the valves to ensure their effectiveness in an emergency.

The heating is provided by an ICOS HE18 Boiler.

There is a Santon premier plus unvented hot water system cylinder within the first floor airing cupboard, which stores hot water for the property.

Getting quotations

The cost of repairs may influence the amount you are prepared to pay for the property. Before you make a legal commitment to buy the property, you should get reports and quotations for all the repairs and further investigations the surveyor may have identified.

You should get at least two quotations from experienced contractors who are properly insured. You should also:

ask them for references from people they have worked for;

describe in writing exactly what you will want them to do; and

get the contractors to put the quotations in writing.

Some repairs will need contractors with specialist skills and who are members of regulated organisations (for example, electricians, gas engineers, plumbers and so on). Some work may also need you to get Building Regulations permission or planning permission from your local authority.

Further investigations

If the surveyor is concerned about the condition of a hidden part of the building, could only see part of a defect or does not have the specialist knowledge to assess part of the property fully, the surveyor may have recommended that further investigations should be carried out to discover the true extent of the problem.

Who you should use for these further investigations

You should ask an appropriately qualified person, though it is not possible to tell you which one. Specialists belonging to different types of organisations will be able to do this. For example, qualified electricians can belong to five different government­approved schemes. If you want further advice, please contact the surveyor.

What the further investigations will involve

This will depend on the type of problem, but to do this properly, parts of the home may have to be disturbed and so you should discuss this matter with the current owner. In some cases, the cost of investigation may be high.

When to do the work

The condition ratings help describe the urgency of the repair and replacement work. The following summary may help you decide when to do the work.

Condition rating 2 ­ repairs should be done soon. Exactly when will depend on the type of problem, but it usually does not have to be done right away. Many repairs could wait weeks or months, giving you time to organise suitable reports and quotations.

Condition rating 3 ­ repairs should be done as soon as possible. The speed of your response will depend on the nature of the problem. For example, repairs to a badly leaking roof or a dangerous gas boiler need to be carried out within a matter of hours, while other less important critical repairs could wait for a few days.

Warning

Although repairs of elements with a condition rating 2 are not considered urgent, if they are not addressed they may develop into defects needing more serious repairs. Flat roofs and gutters are typical examples. These can quickly get worse without warning and result in serious leaks. As a result, you should regularly check elements with a condition rating 2 to make sure they are not getting worse.
